Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Drain and rinse the @sweetcorn{1%pack} and @red kidney beans{1%pack} in a
#sieve{}.

Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{1}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled) (or use a #garlic press{}).

> Kids can help to drain the kidney beans and sweetcorn.

Place a #pot{} over medium-high heat (without oil).

Once hot, fry the @Irish pork mince{240%g} until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw mince. Mince is
> cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks. Season with @salt{to taste} and
@pepper{to taste}.

Add the garlic and @Mexican style spice mix{2%sachets} (with a drizzle of
@oil{to taste} if needed).

Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @chopped tomato with onion & garlic{1%pack}, corn, kidney beans,
@salt{1/4%tsp} and @sugar{1/2%tsp}.

> Double salt and sugar for 4p.

Bring to the boil, cover and simmer for ~{6-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pop the @tortilla{8} into the #oven{} to warm, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once cooked, season the pork to taste with salt and pepper.

Loosen the sauce with a splash of @water{} if necessary.

Stir in as much of the @dried chilli flakes{1%sachet} as you like
(use less if you don't like spice—or if you're cooking for kids).

Divide the pork chilli between #bowls{}, topped with a dollop of
@creme fraiche{65%g}.

Scatter the @grated cheese{50%g} and scallion over the top.

Serve warm tortillas alongside.